  "prompt": "What is GST? And what are the advantages and disadvantages of GST?",
  "response": "GST (Goods and Services Tax) is a comprehensive, multi-stage, destination-based tax levied on the supply of goods and services. Here are its advantages and disadvantages:\n\nAdvantages of GST:\n\n1. Simplified Tax Structure\n- Replaced multiple indirect taxes\n- Reduced tax complexity\n- Single unified tax system\n\n2. Reduced Tax Burden\n- Eliminated cascading tax effects\n- Lowered overall tax rates\n- Reduced tax-on-tax transactions\n\n3. Enhanced Transparency\n- Online filing and tracking\n- Reduced tax evasion\n- Better tax compliance\n\n4. Improved Economic Efficiency\n- Seamless interstate movement of goods\n- Reduced logistics costs\n- Simplified supply chain management\n\n5. Increased Government Revenue\n- Broader tax base\n- Improved tax collection mechanism\n- Better tracking of transactions\n\nDisadvantages of GST:\n\n1. Implementation Challenges\n- Initial compliance difficulties\n- Complex registration processes\n- Technology and infrastructure requirements\n\n2. Higher Compliance Costs\n- Increased paperwork\n- Additional financial burden on businesses\n- Regular filing requirements\n\n3. Impact on Small Businesses\n- Higher compliance costs\n- Limited resources for technology adoption\n- Potential competitive disadvantage\n\n4. Initial Economic Disruption\n- Short-term economic adjustment\n- Temporary business uncertainty\n- Transition challenges\n\n5. Potential Inflationary Pressures\n- Price adjustments\n- Initial increase in certain goods/services prices\n- Consumer adaptation period",
